1 Section 5. Section 13-10-501, MCA, is amended to read:
2 "13-10-501. Petition for nomination by independent candidates or political parties not eligible
3 to participate in primary election. (1) Except as provided in 13-10-504, nominations for public office by an
4 independent candidate or a political party that does not meet the requirements of 13-10-601 may be made by
5 filing a declaration of intent and paying the filing fee in accordance with 13-10-201 and by circulating a petition
6 for nomination.
7 (2) The petition must contain the same information and the oath of the candidate required for a
8 declaration for nomination.
9 (3) If a petition is filed by a political party, it must contain the party name and, in five words or less,
10 the principle that the body represents.
11 (4) The form of the petition must be prescribed by the secretary of state, and the secretary of state
12 shall furnish sample copies to the election administrators and on request to any individual.
13 (5) Each sheet of a petition must contain signatures of electors residing in only one county.
14 (6) An unsuccessful candidate for office at a primary election may not seek nomination by write-in
15 vote or petition for the same office at the general election."
16
17 Section 6. Section 13-10-502, MCA, is amended to read:
18 "13-10-502. Signature requirements for petition. (1) The petition for nomination must be signed by
19 active electors as defined in 13-1-101 residing within the state and district or political subdivision in which the
20 officer or officers are to be elected. Each signature line must contain spaces for the signature, post-office
21 address, and printed last name of the signer.
22 (2) The number of signatures must be 5% 15% 5% or more of the total vote cast for the successful
23 candidate for the same office at the last general election.
24 (3) If the office sought is a new office or the boundaries of the district or political subdivision in
25 which the election is to be held have changed since the last election for the office, the officer with whom
26 nominations for the office sought are filed shall determine the number of signatures required for a petition of
27 nomination for that office. The number of signatures may not be less than is required in subsection (2)."
